{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_beiderbecke_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280657505/1924032301/0098.xml":{"full_text":"DECLARES FEELING\ni OF PANIC ABSENT\nTire Firm Executive Says\nBusiness Outlook Con\ntinues Bright.\nAKRON, Ohio. March 22.\u2014\"A year\n*go tho business man of this country\nWas panicky, looking for the ghost of\ndepression. It took almost nothing\nto stampede the country and put it\ninto a backward frame of mind from\nthe business standpoint. But today\nthe rank and tile of business does not\nfeel panicky.\u201d\nSo declared E. Cl. 'Wilmcr, chairman\nof the board of directors of the Good\nyear Tire and Rubber Company, in an\naddress before 300 members of the\nEast Akron Board of Trade.\n\"Today business men and industries\nare operating on normal require\nments to a greater degree than for\nyears past, and out of that has come\nthe stability and progress and peace\nof mind that the country as a whole\nhas today,\" he continued.\nSubstantiating his statements, Mr.\nWilmer gave figures to show that\nimprovement in business since the\ndepression in 1920 has been gradual 1\nbut effective, pointing out that\n1 hough building suffered a temporal\nsetback in the early part of 1923, it\nmade good gains over the year pre\nvious, and stands in a normal posi\ntion today: that retail business had\n'nereased from 10 to 25 per cent dur\ning the year; that business failures\nwere fewer in 1923 than in the year\nprevious; that tax reform is in sight,\nand that the public debt has been de\ncreased.\nExports Overrated.\n\"Many have had the impression.\"\nMr. Wilmer said, \"that the prosperity\nof the country depends on the export\ntrade, f'onsidered that the total ex\nport volume of business in dollars in\n1923 was four billions, as against a\ngross normal domestic business vary\ning from 55 to 118 billions, impartial\njudgment would say that export busi\nness does not materially affect the\ngeneral trend of affairs, nor would I\nIt put us in a depression or cause in- j\nslated conditions, cn the other hand.\n\"However, we are back today to\nfavorable trade balance with the rest\nof the world.\"\nCommenting on immigration re\nstrictions, Mr. Wilmer stated that\nthough the quota for the present\nfiscal year was already filled in Jan\nuary. the labor problem was solving\nitself in the general adjustment in\nindustries and the taking out of su\nperfluous men equalizing the supply\nby redistribution.\nSees Mental Side.\n\"Xinetcen-twenty-thrce was a year\nof general business adjustment and\naccomplishment.\" the Goodyear exe\ncutive said. \"I believe Coue's doc\ntrine can be applied to business. Be\nlieve conditions are going to he bet\nter, and it will go a long ways\ntoward helping you accomplish the\nends that such bettered conditions\nwill bring. But let suspicion crop in\namong a group of business men in\none section of the country. Let them\nget an idea that tho slock market\nwill fall off or that some other thing\nwill happen, and the idea spreads\nlike wildfire, with the. result that\nEnthusiastic Motorists Call\nThe Chrysler Six\nThe Measure of All Other Cars\nUnbounded interest in the Chrysler Six con* The wonder is, they say, that from a motor\ndnues unabated. only 3-inch bore by 4%\u2019tach stroke you get\nNever has a car been received with such cn- 68 horse power, top speed well over 70 miles\nthusiasm in its initial appearance in this city; an hour, gasoline economy safely 20 miles\nnever before have there been such expressions per gallon, acceleration that is electrifying,\nof wonder and admiration.\nEvery motorist who ha, followed a study of The verdlc *e Chryder Six ia now the\nthe Chrysler Six with a thorough test on the measure of all other cars m every phase of\nroad, agrees that the boldest possible claims performance.\nd^^dT\u201c y 2 f r thiS the mOSt Such a overwhelming number of people am\nAll appreciate that its designer, and builders, she5 he C irys,er SU\nby reason of their intensive study and develop* disappointments have been unavoidable. It\nment of tried and true automotive principles, ucccssary to give all demonstrations in the\nhave produced a car unlike any other in ex* order in which applications are filed. There*\nistence. fore, book yourself at once.\nH. B. LEARY, Jr.\n_ Distributor\nSalesroom MwweU-Chrysfcr-Ctalmers Q c Service Dtpt\n-1321 14th Street North 4296 1612 U Street N.W.\nSalesroom Open Evenings and Sundays\nwJPivn\u00a7tm(*ij&iho*gkpelluliCr/\u00a7igs\nA\nRight Hand Turn\nOver White Line\nMay Save Scolding\nWhen you have accidentally crossed\nthe white line on the street intersec\ntion and you know that the officer is\ngoing to bawl you out for it. don\u2019t\ntry to back up if there are other cars\nbehind you. They'll start blowing\ntheir horns and attract attention to\nyou. which is exactly what you want\nto avoid. It may take you a little out\nof your way, but if it will save a\ncall down\u201d make a right-hand turn if\nyou\u2019ve crossed the Ijne. It\u2019s usually\npermissible.\nSEE BALLOON TIRE\nAS EASIER ON ROAD\nObservers Think Highways Will\nBe Conserved by Broader\nWearing Surface.\nThe balloon tire is as yet 100 new\nto tell its own story, but some of the\nreasons urged against it by its op\nponents do not seem warranted by\nfacts. Misled, perhaps, by the un\ndoubted fact that the pneumatic tire\ncaused great destruction to the then\ncommon type of hard road, the water- j\nj bound macadam, conservatives now\ni state that the balloon tire, with its\ngro-atly increased size of wearing sur\nface. will cause damage to roads of\nother than cement or brick surface.\nThis is not borne out by facts al\nready recorded of other wide-tlre\nbearing surfaces. Heavy trucks,\nequipped with double wheels and flat,\nsolid tires, do no damage to the sur\nface and the highways they use.\nwhether that surface be oil-treated or\ntar-impregnated stone. sand-clay,\nshell, concrete, brick or cement. Hoad\ndamage done by such vehicles is from\nblows or pressure and not from sur\nface wear. It is. with the modern\nroad, almost always the weight or the\nblow which damages the road and\nseldom or never the abrasion of the\nsurface.\nmen get back into their shells and\nbusiness gets a setback.\nI \"If the automobile industry had a\nstruggle in the readjustment period\n1 the rubber industry has passed\nthrough all that and more.\" Mr. Wil\nmer said. \u201cNot only did it have the\nills of the times, but it had a de\ncrease in demand to cope with as\nwell, due to the fact that about this\ntime, because of the greater mileage\nthat tires were giving, the tire con\nsumption per ear dropped four to\ntwo and one-quarter.\"\nMr. Wilmer said that the corporate\nbusiness of the country in dollars\nand cents from 1916 to the present\ntime was $35.000.0000.000 in 1916. with\nearnings of 22 per cent; 1917 touched\n$84,000,000,000 and earned 12 per\ncent: 1918 totaled $86,000,000,000, and\nearnings had dwindled to S per eent,\nand thin baek to $55.00,000.000 in\n1921. when the earnings were less\nthan 1 per cent.\n\u201cThese conditions forced a read\njustment throughout industry,\" he\nsaid. \"A new study of every item of\nexpense of every factor effecting ef\nficiency.\n\"Every concern lived a lifetime in\nthat short span since the colossal in\ndustrial crash of 1920, and, though no\nman can definitely forecast the fu\nture, the future seems bright.\"\nTHE IS UNDAY tSTAR, WASHINGTON, D. (J., MARCH 23, 1924-PAIiT 3.\nFUTURE OF AUTO\nFORESEEN BY FORO\nProphecy by Noted Manu\nfacturer, Made in 1910,\nNow Held as Verified.\nHow clearly Henry Ford saw the\nj lulure of the automobile and how\ni well he prophesied it is shown in an\nI article written by him in February,\nj 1910. and published in a Detroit news-\nI paper.\nIn 1909, as the article states. 2,000,-\n000 horse-drawn vehicles were sold\nas against 80,000 automobiles. How\nthe prophesied reversal came appears\nin figures for last year, which show\nthe sale of approximately 4,000.000\nmotor cars during 1923 as compared\nwith 100,000 horse-drawn vehicles.\nText of Ford\u2019) Article.\nThe article follows:\n\"The automobile of the past at\ntained success in spite of its price,\nbecause there were more than enough\npurchasers to be found to fake the\nlimited output of the then new indus\ntry. Proportionately few could buy,\nbut these few could keep all the man\nufacturers busy, and price therefore\nhad no bearing on sales.\n\u201cThe automobile of the present is\nmaking good because the price has\nbeen reduced just enough to add suf\nficient new purchasers to take care\nof the increased output. Supply and\ndemand, not cost, has regulated the\nselling price of automobiles. The car\nof today is better by far than the car\nof a few years ago\u2014the natural re\nsult of experience. The price is lower,\njust enough lower to add sufficient\npossible purchasers to buy the in\ncreased output.\n\"The automobile of the future must\nhe enough better than the present car\nto beget confidence in the man of\nlimited means and enough lowor In\nprice to insure sales for the enor\nmously increased output.\nMust Be \"Car of the People.\"\n\"The car of the future must be \u2018the\ncar for the people,\u2019 the car that any\nman can own who can afford a horse\nand carriage; and. mark my words,\nthat car is coming sooner than most\npeople expect.\n\"In the low-priced car dwells the\nfuture success of the automobile.\nComparatively few persons can afford\neven a SI,OOO car. A limited number\nof factories can easily supply ail the\ndemand for high-priced cars, but the\nmarket for a low-priced car is un\nlimited. More than 2.000,000 horse\ndrawn vehicles were sold by Ameri\ncan factories in 1909. When you sub\nstitute a motor-driven vehicle for\neach of these 2.000,000 wagons and\ncarriages, you get an idea of the\nautomobile of the future.\n\"The low-priced car will not be a\nmakeshift, an automobile by cour\ntes>. a machine built for a price. It\nis harder to sell to a man who can\nonly afford a low-priced car than to\nthe man whose money comes more\neasily. Not only must the successful\ncar of the future be low-priced, but\nit must present at least equal value\nwith the present high-priced cars.\n\"The low-priced car should actually\nbe better than the car at a higher\nprice, for more is expected of it. The\nman who can afford the high-priced\ncar can afford a man to keep it in\norder, while the man who has to buy\nTest of Brakes\nBest Safeguard\nFor Auto Owner\nIn tbrm* days when the cost of\nautomobile Insurance Is being\u2019 given\nserious consideration, motorists\nshould be Interested In the following\nabatement issued by the national\nbrake inspection movement, a country\nwide campaigned designed to induce\nautomobile owners to have their brakes\ntested by competent mechanic* at reg\nular intervals;\n\u201cI represent the lowent kind of\naccident, health and liability in\nsurance. If you have one of my\npolicies I will protect you against\nnervous breakdown, serious n.iahaia\nand even death. I can also keep you\nout of annoying arguments, ex\npensive law suits and jail.\n\u201cBefore receiving one of my poli\ncies you must subscribe to my rules\nand regulations. They are very\nsimple and may be summed up in\njust two words\u2014common sense. You\nmust also agree to have a thorough\nexamination by an expert at least\ntwice a year. Tour premiums will be\ngreatly reduced because of less risk\nIf these examinations are made\nquarterly.\n\u201cPolicies may be taken out any\ntime, regardless of the age, occupa\ntion or residence of the assured.\n\u201cInsure today, tomorrow may be\ntoo late.\n\u201cI am a slogan.\n\"My name is:\n\"Brake inspection\u2014your protection.\u201d\ntion.\u201d\nPolice officials, safety councils, mo\ntoring clubs and chambers of com\nmerce in more than 200 cities have\nshown an Interest in the national\nbrake-inspection movement, a coun\ntry-wide campaign designed to Induce\nmotorists to have their automobile\nbrakes tested by competent mechan\nics at periodic intervals.\nDon\u2019t try to blow the jay walker\nout of your way. Use your brakes.\nAre pour automobile brakes break\ning the law? Have them tested today.\na low-priced car. if any, has to look\nafter it himself, whether or not he\nhas any mechanical ability. Like\nwise, when he buys, he buys for\nbusiness use and pleasure, too. That\ncondition prevails today. The low\npriced car must be better built than\nthe higher priced product, because it\nreceives harder use. The successful\nlow-priced car of today la successful\nbecause it stands harder usage than\nIs accorded to |5,000 creations.\nUs Ipkeep Coat Kssentlal.\n\u201cEqually important with low cost\nas a qualification of the car of the\nfuture is 'low cost of upkeep.' The\nweekly expense of an automobile will\nbe more important to the man whose\nIncome is |IOO a month than will the\ncost price. The one he has saved by\neasy stages, the other must be taken\nout of his earnings. Gasoline bills,\nrepair bills, tire bills must be low.\nThey should be as low as the expense\nbills for a horse and carriage. This\nlow maintenance account can result\nonly from light weight.\n\"So the car of the future will be\nlight as well as low-priced. This\nmeans the substitution of quality for\nquantity, even to the use of mate\nrials not yet discovered.\u201d\nIt Is notable also in connection with\nthe foregoing prophecy by Mr. Ford,\nthat during the last year 2,090,959\nFord cars and trucks were produced,\nfulfilling the statement made In 1910\nthat the light, low-priced car would\nenjoy the greatest popularity.\nBRIGHT OUTLOOK\nFOR CAR TOURISTS\nBecreation Seekers in California to\nHave Pathway Made Easy,\nAuto Club Announces.\nLOS ANGELES. Calif., March 22.\nRecreation seekers in California this\nreanon will find their pathway made\ntojty, according to announcement\nfrom the outing bureau of the Auto\nmobile dub of Southern California.\nThose who heed the call of the open\nroad will have available a complete\ncompilation of hunting and fishing\ntrips* hiking jaunts, camping spots,\nscenic novelties and all that tends to\nmake life joyous in. the great out\ndoors\nThe mass of maps and data repre\nsents more thao a year's work, in\nwhich the co-operation of more than\n100 forest rangers in California's sev\nenteen national forests was enlisted\nEighteen separate maps have been\nprepared, designating fishing streams,\nhunting preserves, supply stations,\ncamp grounds hotels garages and\nevery other item of interest to the\nmotor tourtsrt.\nIn addition there are fourteen bul\nletins covering in detail the more ac\ncessible of the national forests, which\nInclude Mount La.ssen, the only ac\ntive volcano in the United States;\nSequoia and Gen. Grunt parks, w here\nare the largest trees in the world;\nTosemlte. with, its wonderful water\nfalls. and the eastern high. Sierras, j\nwhich include Mount Whitney, the\npeak, of which rears its head M.IiO?\nfeet In the sky, where it Majids su\npremo as the higlwsl point in the\nT.'nitod States and overlooks the floor\nof Death valley, the lowest point be\nlow sea level on the continent.\nThis recreation service is extended\nfree to visiting motorists by the\nAutomobile Club of Southern Oali- 1\nfornla, which maintains twenty-nine\nbranches in the southern part of the\nMate, in addition to headquarters in\nLos Angeiea.\nBlind Girl Stenographer.\nMiss Dora Bernstein, formerly a\nstudent at the School for the Blind\nin Batavia, N. Y., has made herself so\nproficient with the typewriter and in\ntaking stenographic notes that she\nhas been awarded a certificate and\nwill engage in commercial work. One\nof her very strong recommendations,\naccording to her tutors, is that she\nis a perfect speller, which is very\nrare among the blind. Miss Bernstein\nalso is equipped for work in a credit\nor insurance firm's office, notwith\nstanding the large amount of figures\nand tabulation necessary.\nNew Sewing-Up Thread Used.\nA surgeon who suffered an accident\nand had a horsehair handy has. with\nthe aid of a scientist in Wisconsin, in\nvented a treated silk that will be even\nbetter, it is maintained. In the past\nhorsehair silver wire, silk worm gut\nand celluloid thread have been used, j\nwith horsehair being the most fa- j\nvored because it stuck less to the I\nflesh and was less painful on ex- j\nI traction. The new suture is made by i\ntreating fine silk thread chemically\nso that tissue cells will not grow to\nit. Prof. Louis Kahlenberg of the\nUniversity of Wisconsin has per- 1\nfected the treatment.\nThis Method Protects You\nThe Hupmobile Parts Display takes you have ever seen, why the Hupmo\nthe mystery out of the motor car. It bile stands up so well, and why some\ngives you the facts that count. other cars are a source of continual\nr> i i t. i i trouble and expense,\nremaps you know little, or nothing,\nof motor car production. When you The Hupmobile way of buying a\nread on this Parts Display how the motor car is the sound, business-like\nHupmobile is built, and then read, way. And it is a liberal education in\ndirectly contrasted with it, what the what makes motor car value.\nmore common construction is, you c i-i\n\u2022ii i vi whether you are going to buy a\nwill select your next car with greater\nj r. i\u00a3 car now, or next year, we advise that\ncare, and greater profit to yourself. J\nyou come in soon and study the\nYou will also see, more clearly than Hupmobile Parts Display.\nSTERRETT FLEMING, Inc.\nChamplain St. and Kalorama Road\nColumbia 5050\nBranch Salesroom, 1223 Conn, Ave.\njiMgrtm j j f\n||gpHp\u00df\u00dfP%k Most Popular\nI llPwh Bm Oldsmobile\nj Ever Built\nI oSince0 Since its announcement last\nn| October, the model 30 Oldamobilc\nSix has achieved a great success,\ny /a The public recognizes the wholly\nj til /n\u00df\u25a0r AW GSmOtSB unusual value offered in this six\u2014\ni|||l|W I a value well typified in the coupe.\njjlU Here